# Implementation Plan: Untrack Vendor Directory

The `vendor/` directory is currently being tracked by Git, which causes persistent conflicts on the production server whenever dependencies are autogenerated or updated. We will remove it from the Git index (untrack it) while keeping the files locally.

## User Review Required

> [!CAUTION]
> **Action Required After Pulling to Production:**
> Once these changes are pushed and you pull them onto your production server, Git will **delete** the `vendor/` directory on the server because it is no longer tracked. 
> You **MUST** run the following command on production immediately after pulling to restore the dependencies:
> ```bash
> composer install --no-dev
> ```

## Proposed Changes

### [Component] Repository Hygiene

#### [EXECUTE] Git Commands
- Run `git rm -r --cached vendor` to remove the directory from the Git index (this does not delete your local files).
- run `git status` to verify `vendor` is now listed as deleted but the files are still present in the filesystem.

#### [MODIFY] [.gitignore](file:///mnt/WebliesNew/CareerWithoutBarrier/career-without-barrier/.gitignore)
- Ensure `/vendor` and `/vendor/**` are present (already confirmed but will verify).

#### [EXECUTE] Commit & Push
- Commit the removal: `git commit -m "Chore: Untrack vendor directory"`
- Push to origin: `git push origin master`

## Open Questions

- Just to confirm, do you have `composer` installed and working on the production server? (You will need it to restore the vendor folder after the pull).

